# Q3.g outliers for bmi
first_quartile = np.percentile(ins_data['bmi'], 25)
third_quartile = np.percentile(ins_data['bmi'], 75)
iqr = third_quartile - first_quartile
print(iqr)
low_lim = first_quartile - 1.5 * iqr 
up_lim =  third_quartile + 1.5 * iqr
print(low_lim,up_lim)
outlier =[] 
for x in ins_data['bmi']: 
    if ((x> up_lim) or (x<low_lim)): 
         outlier.append(x) 
# print(' outlier in the dataset is', outlier)
print(' no. of outliers are', len(outlier))

 no. of outliers are 9

The bmi has very few outliers, as indicated by the count above.This is also verifiable in the boxplot. This indicates that considering the distribution there are only 9 people who are beyond the cut off value.

Q 4a Do charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't.

With hypothesis testing using the t test we can find whether there is a relationship between smoking and non smoking charges.
Null Hypothesis is The charges are same for smoker and non smoker
Alternate Hypothesis is That the charges are either greater or less but not equal (not same).

In [169]:
ins_data.head()
Out[169]:
age sex bmi children smoker region charges
0 19 female 27.900 0 yes southwest 16884.92400
1 18 male 33.770 1 no southeast 1725.55230
2 28 male 33.000 3 no southeast 4449.46200
3 33 male 22.705 0 no northwest 21984.47061
4 32 male 28.880 0 no northwest 3866.85520
In [175]:
smokers = np.array(ins_data[ins_data["smoker"]=="yes"].charges)
non_smokers = np.array(ins_data[ins_data["smoker"]=="no"].charges)
t_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(smokers,non_smokers)
print(t_statistic,p_value)

46.664921172723716 8.271435842177219e-283

The p value is much less than .025. Using .025 as the charges can differ in either direction. The null hypothesis has to be rejected. The non smokers pay much less charges than the smokers

Q4.b. Does bmi of males differ significantly from that of females?
Again using the same approach as above we formulate the null and alternative hypothesis and doing a t test to conclude whether to accept or reject null hypothesis
Null Hypothesis - bmi remains same for males and females
Alternate Hypothesis - bmi is different for males and females(either greater or less)

In [176]:
female = np.array(ins_data[ins_data["sex"]=="female"].bmi)
male = np.array(ins_data[ins_data["sex"]=="male"].bmi)
t_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(female,male)
print(t_statistic,p_value)

-1.696752635752224 0.08997637178984932

The p value is higher than .05. Hence we cannot reject the Null Hypothesis.

Q 4.c. Is the proportion of smokers significantly different in different genders? We can use the z test of proportions to determine whether the smokers for different genders have different proportions
Null Hypothesis : The proportions are same Alternate Hypothesis : The proportions are different

In [181]:
female_smokers = ins_data[ins_data["sex"]=='female'].smoker.value_counts()[1]
male_smokers = ins_data[ins_data["sex"]=='male'].smoker.value_counts()[1]
males = ins_data.sex.value_counts()[0]
females = ins_data.sex.value_counts()[1]
print([female_smokers, male_smokers] , [females, males])
print(f' Proportion of smokers in females, males = {round(115/662,2)}%, {round(159/676,2)}% respectively')

[115, 159] [662, 676]
 Proportion of smokers in females, males = 0.17%, 0.24% respectively

The proportions seem to be different but we have to check if they are statistically significant

In [184]:
t_stats, p_val = proportions_ztest([female_smokers,male_smokers],[females,males])
print(t_stats,p_val)

-2.7867402154855503 0.005324114164320532

As the p value is much less than the value of .05 we can reject the null hypothesis

Q 4.d. Is the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children, the same?
The problem falls into the category of comparing multiple groups and therefore a candidate for Oneway Anova.
Null Hypothesis : "the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children are same"
Alternate Hypothesis: "the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children are different"

ins_data.head()

stats.levene(female_no_child, female_one_child, female_two_child)

LeveneResult(statistic=0.9433311607108589, pvalue=0.3899432394522804)
In [210]:
stats.shapiro(female_no_child), stats.shapiro(female_one_child), stats.shapiro(female_two_child)
Out[210]:
(ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9896312355995178, pvalue=0.03757598251104355),
 ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9921025037765503, pvalue=0.5361911654472351),
 ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9860439300537109, pvalue=0.2596229910850525))

The assumptions for implementing one way ANOVA include (as in independent sample t-test):
The normality criterion: each group compared should come from a population following the normal distribution.
The variance criterion (or 'homogeneity of variances'): samples should come from populations with the same variance.
Independent samples: performance (the dependent variable) in each sample should not be affected by the conditions in other samples.
The levene test indicates that p value is greater than threshold a = 0.05, therefore we can conclude that samples come from populations with the same variance
The shapiro test indicates that
samples come from populations that follow normal distribution. If the pvalue for shapiro result is greater than the threshold of .05 we can conclude that
Please note that the female_no_child p value is .03 and is less than the threshold.

In [212]:
F, p = stats.f_oneway(female_no_child,female_one_child,female_two_child)
print(F,p)

0.3344720147757968 0.7158579926754841

The p value is greater than the alpha value and hence we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children are not different or there is no effect of number of children on the bmi in females.
